# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alkane
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alkane/1-3-5-triethylbenzene] 1,3,5-Triethylbenzene can be prepared by a Friedel-Crafts alkylation of benzene with ethyl bromide in presence of aluminium chloride.
[src:alkane/1-3-5-triethylbenzene] 1,3,5-Triethylbenzene is a flammable, hard to ignite, colorless liquid that is almost insoluble in water.
[src:alkane/1-3-5-triethylbenzene] 1,3,5-Triethylbenzene can be used in synthesis of a series of di- and trinucleating ligands.
[src:alkane/1-3-5-triethylbenzene] The vapour of 1,3,5-Triethylbenzene can form an explosive mixture with air (flash point: 76 °C).
[src:alkane/1-5-hexadiene] The catalyst is derived from Re2O7 on alumina.
[src:alkane/1-7-octadiene] Structurally related octadienes bearing two methyl groups are of commercial interest.
[src:alkane/1-7-octadiene] Such compounds are produced by pyrolysis of pinane, which is abundantly available from terpentine or related wood-derived chemicals.
[src:alkane/1-7-octadiene] The diene has also been the subject of many research papers.
[src:alkane/1-7-octadiene] For example, with ethylene it undergoes a cross-enyne metathesis Diels–Alder reaction.
[src:alkane/1-7-octadiene] It undergoes ring-closing metathesis to give cyclooctene.
[src:alkane/1-7-octadiene] Plasma polymerized 1,7-octadiene films deposited on silica can produce particles with tuned hydrophobicity.
[src:alkane/1-methylcyclopropene] The compound **1-methylcyclopropene**, also known as **1-MCP**, is a cyclo­propene derivative used as a synthetic plant growth regulator.
[src:alkane/1-methylcyclopropene] It is structurally related to the natural plant hormone ethylene and it is used commercially to slow down the ripening of fruit and to help maintain the freshness of cut flowers.
[src:alkane/1-methylcyclopropene] The phenyl­lithium should be free of lithium halides.
[src:alkane/1-methylcyclopropene] The corresponding reaction of allyl chloride and phenyl­lithium main affords cyclo­propyl­benzene.
[src:alkane/1-methylcyclopropene] The mechanism of action of 1-MCP involves its tightly binding to the ethylene receptor in plants, thereby blocking the effects of ethylene (competitive inhibitor).
[src:alkane/1-methylcyclopropene] The compound 1-MCP is used commercially to maintain the freshness of ornamental plants and flowers and preventing the ripening of fruits.
[src:alkane/1-methylcyclopropene] It is used in enclosed sites, such as coolers, truck trailers, greenhouses, storage facilities, and shipping containers.
[src:alkane/1-methylcyclopropene] Under the brand name EthylBloc, 1-MCP was approved in 1999 by the U.S.
[src:alkane/1-methylcyclopropene] Environmental Protection Agency for use on ornamental crops.
[src:alkane/1-methylcyclopropene] For cut flowers, potted flowers, and bedding, nursery and foliage plants, 1-MCP prevents or delays wilting, leaf yellowing, opening, and death.
[src:alkane/1-methylcyclopropene] Under the brand name SmartFresh, 1-MCP is used in the agriculture industry by growers, packers, and shippers to prevent or delay the natural ripening process.
[src:alkane/1-methylcyclopropene] The use of 1-MCP in agricultural products including apples, kiwifruit, tomatoes, bananas, plums, persimmons, avocados, and melons has been approved and accepted for use in more than 34 countries including the European Union and the United States.
[src:alkane/1-methylcyclopropene] Although benefiting from fresher produce and lower cost, the consumer however may be purchasing fruit that is older than expected.
[src:alkane/1-methylcyclopropene] The compound 1-MCP is also being developed as a crop protection technique.
[src:alkane/1-methylcyclopropene] By spraying 1-MCP on growing field crops during times of stress, the crops may be protected from moderate heat and drought conditions.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] The first example of a stable heteroalkene E=C or E=E' (E, E' = P) containing a heavy group 15 element was reported in 1982 by Yoshifuji.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] After the realization of heavier heteroalkenes, the field of organometallic chemistry began exploring the idea of heteroallenes E=C=E' and E=C=C=E', in which one or more carbon atom of an allene is substituted by a heavier atom.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] The first of these heteroallenes containing a heavier group 15 element to be reported was synthesized in 1984 by Yoshifuji.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] 1-phosphaallene, also referred to as ethenylidenephosphine or λ3-phosphaallene, was first synthesized using the 2,4,6-tri-t-butylphenyl (supermesityl, or Mes*) moiety as a sterically protecting group.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] The most widely known example of 1-phosphaalenes is the Mes* substituted 3H-phosphallene, where a hydrogen is bonded to the terminal carbon atom, which was synthesized by Märkl and Reitinger in 1988.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] Some more recent advances made in regards to 1-phosphaallenes include the development of simpler synthetic routes and the discovery of synthetic pathways using phosphaallenes to create molecules that are typically only synthesized through complicated methods.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] Multiple synthetic routes to 1-phosphaallenes have been reported.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] The most common are Phospha-Wittig-Horner reactions, rearrangement of alkylynlphosphines with a base present, dehydrochlorination of a chlorovinylphospine, and the reaction of lithium with a C,C-dichlorophosphirane.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] More recent synthetic advances include the dehydrobromination of phosphaalkenes the hydroalumination of alkynylphosphines.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] The Phospha-Wittig-Horner reaction, first reported by Mathey et al. in 1992, was initially developed as a synthetic route to convert aldehydes and ketones into C-mono and C,C-disubstituted phosphaalkenes, respectively.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] This method was then adapted to rapidly synthesize phosphaallenes by reacting phosphaketenes with an organolithium base, such as lithium diisopropylamide or t-BuOLi.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] n-BuLi is used as a strong base in the synthesis of a phosphaallene.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] A lithium complex can be used to synthesize phosphaallenes.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] Like the transition from an alkyne to an allene in organic chemistry, phosphaallenes can be synthesized from alkynylphosphines by adding a strong base such as n-butyllithium (n-BuLi).
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] These complexes are typically useful due to the broad range of stable products that can be obtained from this synthetic route.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] Multiple stable phosphaallenes have been synthesized from LiC≡CR and ArP(H)Cl (R = Ph, t-Bu, Me, CH2OSiMe3).
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] The basicity of the lithium complex is essential to the success of these reactions.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] The dehydrochlorination of 1-chlorovinylphosphine by DBU (1,8-diazabicyclo-[5.4.0]undec-7-ene) yields a variety of results, depending on the structure of the initial chlorovinylphosphine.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] Many of these reactions require temperatures between −90 °C and 0 °C to ensure a stable product is formed.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] As many of these reactions are warmed, oligomerization of the phosphaallene occurs.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] Other reactions following this synthetic route occur with gas phase reagents at 250 °C.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] In this synthetic route, a dichlorocarbene is first reacted with a phosphaethylene.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] The addition of t-BuLi to the resulting 2,2-dichlorophosphirane yields the phosphaallene.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] This route includes an insertion of carbon into the P=C bond of a phosphaalkene.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] (Z)-2,5-dibromo-1-phosphapent-1-ene with the sterically cumbersome Mes* moiety was reacted with t-BuOK to yield the cyclopropylidenephosphaethene product.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] Treatment of the (Z)-2,5-dibromo-1-phosphapent-1-ene reagent with a weaker base, EtONa yields a non-cyclic isomer that can undergo cyclization in the presence of t-BuOK.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] In 2019, a new synthetic route for the synthesis of phosphaallenes was reported by Klöcker and coworkers.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] The hydroalumination of dialkynylphosphines with different alkylaluminium hydrides resulted in the elimination of dialkylaluminium alkynides and the desired phosphaallenes.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] Many of the phosphaallenes Klöcker and coworkers synthesized spontaneously decomposed into less-desired products, but the newly reported synthetic method did allow for the isolation of some highly reactive compounds that had not been isolated previously.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] In 2022, the most notable aspect of 1-phosphaallenes is their reactivity.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] Phosphaallenes contain three reactive centers: the P=C bond, the C=C bond, and the phosphorus atom.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] The P=C bond and the C=C bond are thought to be electronically independent of one another.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] This gives rise to a wide variety of reactivity, which is similar to that of phosphaalkenes.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] Without a large steric hindrance, most phosphaallenes quickly dimerize in a [2+2]- or [2+3]-cycloaddition to yield four- or five-membered rings.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] Thus, in order to prevent dimerization, a bulky moiety such as Mes* is often used.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] Dimerization frequently occurs in a head-to-tail manner, exhibiting coupling between either the two C=C bonds or the two P=C bonds.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] The regioselectivity of these dimerization reactions depends on the substituents on the C in the 3 position.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] Nucleophilic alkoxide as well as n-BuLi will add to the P=C bond of a phosphaallene.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] As seen in the reaction scheme, the central C atom is the preferred location for proton attack due to the partial negative charge it possesses.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] The reaction of phosphaallenes with dichlorocarbenes results in a [2+1]-cycloaddition to the P=C double bond, which results in stable heterocyclic compounds.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] Phosphaallenes have also been investigated as reagents to form carbenes.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] Reacting the phosphaallene H2P=C=PH with acetylene yields a carbene via [3 + 2]-cycloaddition.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] Crystal structure showing phosphaallene-transition metal coordination.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] Phosphaallenes can coordinate in an ɳ1 or ɳ2 fashion depending on the metal and experimental conditions.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] Recent studies into the coordination behavior of the 3H-phosphaallene with tungsten (W) show that both stable and unstable phosphaallenes can bond to W through and ɳ1-coordination mode via a P-W bond.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] Due to the stabilizing effect of coordination, reacting transient phosphaallenes with W has become a common method to create stable phosphaallenes that can then be characterized.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] These studies have also demonstrated that 3H-phosphaallenes exhibit ɳ2-coordination to Pt via side-on overlap between Pt and the P=C double bond resulting in a three-membered PtPC heterocycle.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] Head-to-tail dimerization of 3H-phosphaallene.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] Tricyclic phosphine resulting from decomposition via irradiation.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] Decomposition of the 3H-phosphaallene occurs at room-temperature to produce several products via P=C (head-to-tail) or C=C dimerization.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] One decomposition pathway results in an unusual tricyclic phosphine which can be selectively formed by irradiating a solution of the phosphaallene, iBu2AlH, and TripP(C≡CtBu)2 in n-hexanes for 60h with a mercury vapor lamp.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] Under these conditions, the tricyclic phosphine was isolated in high yield and a purity of >95%.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] Recently, two novel 1-benzodihydrophosphetes were synthesized by heating 3H-phosphaallene Mes*P=C=C(H)R (R = tBu, Ad) in toluene at 110 °C for 16-20h.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] The resulting 1- benzodihydrophosphetes were not stable unless coordinated to tungsten.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] The phosphorus-bound H of the product can be used in catalyst-free hydrophosphination reactions and in the synthesis of bulky phosphine ligands.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] Hydroboration is used as a method to reduce unsaturated compounds, and has been used to reduce P-C double or triple bonds in phosphaalkenes and phosphaalkynes.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] Hydroboration of the 3H-phosphaallene Mes*-P=C=C(H)-tBu with 1:1 molar ratio of phosphaallene to H3B(SMe2) yielded a di(phosphaalkenyl)borane, and the reaction in 2:1 molar ratio of phosphaallene to H3B(SMe2) yielded the desired product with a B atom bound to two P=C double bonds.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] The hydroboration of the C=C bond was preferred over the hydroboration of the P=C bond.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] Phosphaallenes are typically colorless or pale yellow in color, and are often crystalline in structure; however, few crystal structures have been reported for this class of compounds.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] One compound, ArP=C=CPh2 (Ar =Mes*) was synthesized and characterized by single crystal X-ray diffraction.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] This compound showed a relatively short P=C double bond length of 1.625(4)Å and a short C=C bond length of 1.1327(5)Å, which closely resembles the bond length in an allene.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] The crystal structure also showed a bent geometry with the P=C=C bond angle at 168.0(3)°.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] This bent geometry is thought to be a result of both steric and electronic effects.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] One possible explanation for the observed bent geometry is the bonding model postulated by Lappert et al. which described the bonding between P and the C as singlet states that act in a double π-donor-acceptor fashion.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] The crystal structure of another 1-phosphaallene RP=C=CHR' (R= Mes*, R' = tBu) displays the same bent geometry with the P=C=C bond angle being reported as 170.7°.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] Further, this compound also contains a short P=C bond length (1.634Å) and a short C=C bond length (1.136Å).
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] The electronic structure of 1-phosphaallene is nearly identical to that of phosphaalkene.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] The HOMO in both molecules is the π-orbital of the C=P bond, which is primarily P in character.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] The LUMO in both structures, is also heavily localized over the C=P bond.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] However, the dipole moment in phosphaallenes is larger than that of phosphaalkenes.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] In compounds with the antisymmetric form X=C=Y, IR stretching bands are observed in the 1600–2300 cm−1 region.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] However, the IR spectra of 1-phosphaallenes do not contain bands in this region, which suggests that the phosphaallene P=C=C is relatively symmetric.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] In the phosphaallene H2C=C=PH, stretching frequencies are observed at 1788 and 789 cm−1, which are attributed to the C=C bond and the C=P bond, respectively.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] In similar compounds containing a C=C=N skeleton, there is a very strong band present within the 1600 – 2300 cm−1 region.
[src:alkane/1-phosphaallenes] The presence of two stretching frequencies rather than one strong frequency in the phosphaallene supports that the C=C and C=P bonds are nearly independent of one another electronically.
[src:alkane/2-2-3-3-tetramethylbutane] The compound can be obtained from ethyl bromide, *tert*-butyl bromide, and magnesium metal in the presence of manganese(II) ions.
[src:alkane/2-2-3-3-tetramethylbutane] Despite conditions amenable to the formation of a Grignard reagent, organomagnesium compounds are believed not to be the active species.
[src:alkane/2-2-3-3-tetramethylbutane] Instead, they transmetalate to organomanganese compounds, which then decompose to *tert*-butyl radicals, which dimerize.
[src:alkane/2-2-3-3-tetramethylbutane] The full IUPAC name of the compound is **2,2,3,3-tetramethylbutane**, but the numbers are superfluous in this case because there is no other possible arrangement of "tetramethylbutane".
[src:alkane/2-2-3-trimethylbutane] It was first synthesized in 1922 by Belgian chemists Georges Chavanne (1875–1941) and B.
[src:alkane/2-2-3-trimethylbutane] Lejeune, who called it **trimethylisopropylmethane**.
[src:alkane/2-2-3-trimethylbutane] Due to its high octane rating (112–113 RON, 101 MON) triptane was produced on alkylation units starting from 1943 for use as an anti-knock additive in gasoline.
[src:alkane/2-2-3-trimethylbutane] It was extensively researched for this role and received the modern name in the late 1930s at a joint laboratory of NACA, National Bureau of Standards, US Army Air Corps and the Bureau of Aeronautics.
[src:alkane/2-2-3-trimethylbutane] As of 2011, it was not a significant component of US automobile gasoline, present only in trace amounts (0.05–0.1%).
[src:alkane/alkane] In organic chemistry, an **alkane**, or **paraffin** (a historical trivial name that also has other meanings), is an acyclic saturated hydrocarbon.
[src:alkane/alkane] In other words, an alkane consists of hydrogen and carbon atoms arranged in a tree structure in which all the carbon–carbon bonds are single.
[src:alkane/alkane] Alkanes have the general chemical formula C*n*H2*n*+2.
[src:alkane/alkane] The alkanes range in complexity from the simplest case of methane (CH4), where *n* = 1 (sometimes called the parent molecule), to arbitrarily large and complex molecules, like hexacontane (C60H122) or 4-methyl-5-(1-methylethyl) octane, an isomer of dodecane (C12H26).
[src:alkane/alkane] The International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) defines alkanes as "acyclic branched or unbranched hydrocarbons having the general formula C*n*H2*n*+2, and therefore consisting entirely of hydrogen atoms and saturated carbon atoms".
[src:alkane/alkane] However, some sources use the term to denote *any* saturated hydrocarbon, including those that are either monocyclic (i.e. the cycloalkanes) or polycyclic, despite them having a distinct general formula (e.g. cycloalkanes are C*n*H2*n*).
[src:alkane/alkane] In an alkane, each carbon atom is sp3-hybridized with 4 sigma bonds (either C–C or C–H), and each hydrogen atom is joined to one of the carbon atoms (in a C–H bond).
[src:alkane/alkane] The longest series of linked carbon atoms in a molecule is known as its carbon skeleton or carbon backbone.
[src:alkane/alkane] The number of carbon atoms may be considered as the size of the alkane.
[src:alkane/alkane] One group of the higher alkanes are waxes, solids at standard ambient temperature and pressure (SATP), for which the number of carbon atoms in the carbon backbone is greater than about 17.
[src:alkane/alkane] Methane is produced by methanogenic archaea and some long-chain alkanes function as pheromones in certain animal species or as protective waxes in plants and fungi.
[src:alkane/alkane] Nevertheless, most alkanes do not have much biological activity.
[src:alkane/alkane] They can be viewed as molecular trees upon which can be hung the more active/reactive functional groups of biological molecules.
[src:alkane/alkane] The alkanes have two main commercial sources: petroleum (crude oil) and natural gas.
[src:alkane/alkane] An alkyl group is an alkane-based molecular fragment that bears one open valence for bonding.
[src:alkane/alkane] They are generally abbreviated with the symbol for any organyl group, R, although Alk is sometimes used to specifically symbolize an alkyl group (as opposed to an alkenyl group or aryl group).
[src:alkane/alkane] Ordinarily, the C–C single bond distance is 1.53 ångströms (1.53×10−10 m).
[src:alkane/alkane] Saturated hydrocarbons can be linear, branched, or cyclic.
[src:alkane/alkane] The third group is sometimes called cycloalkanes.
[src:alkane/alkane] Very complicated structures are possible by combining linear, branched, cyclic alkanes.
[src:alkane/alkane] Alkanes with more than three carbon atoms can be arranged in various ways, forming structural isomers.
[src:alkane/alkane] The simplest isomer of an alkane is the one in which the carbon atoms are arranged in a single chain with no branches.
[src:alkane/alkane] This isomer is sometimes called the *n*-isomer (*n* for "normal", although it is not necessarily the most common).
[src:alkane/alkane] However, the chain of carbon atoms may also be branched at one or more points.
[src:alkane/alkane] The number of possible isomers increases rapidly with the number of carbon atoms.
[src:alkane/alkane] For example, 3-methylhexane and its higher homologues are chiral due to their stereogenic center at carbon atom number 3.
[src:alkane/alkane] The above list only includes differences of connectivity, not stereochemistry.
[src:alkane/alkane] In addition to the alkane isomers, the chain of carbon atoms may form one or more rings.
[src:alkane/alkane] Such compounds are called cycloalkanes, and are also excluded from the above list because changing the number of rings changes the molecular formula.
[src:alkane/alkane] For example, cyclobutane and methylcyclopropane are isomers of each other (C4H8), but are not isomers of butane (C4H10).
[src:alkane/alkane] Branched alkanes are more thermodynamically stable than their linear (or less branched) isomers.
[src:alkane/alkane] For example, the highly branched 2,2,3,3-tetramethylbutane is about 1.9 kcal/mol more stable than its linear isomer, *n*-octane.
[src:alkane/alkane] The IUPAC nomenclature (systematic way of naming compounds) for alkanes is based on identifying hydrocarbon chains.
[src:alkane/alkane] Unbranched, saturated hydrocarbon chains are named systematically with a Greek numerical prefix denoting the number of carbons and the suffix "-ane".
[src:alkane/alkane] In 1866, August Wilhelm von Hofmann suggested systematizing nomenclature by using the whole sequence of vowels a, e, i, o and u to create suffixes -ane, -ene, -ine (or -yne), -one, -une, for the hydrocarbons C*n*H2*n*+2, C*n*H2*n*, C*n*H2*n*−2, C*n*H2*n*−4, C*n*H2*n*−6.
[src:alkane/alkane] In modern nomenclature, the first three specifically name hydrocarbons with single, double and triple bonds; while "-one" now represents a ketone.
[src:alkane/alkane] Straight-chain alkanes are sometimes indicated by the prefix *n*- (for "normal") where a non-linear isomer exists.
[src:alkane/alkane] Alternative names for this group used in the petroleum industry are **linear paraffins** or ***n*-paraffins**.
[src:alkane/alkane] The first four names were derived from methanol, ether, propionic acid and butyric acid.
[src:alkane/alkane] Alkanes with five or more carbon atoms are named by adding the suffix **-ane** to the appropriate numerical multiplier prefix with elision of any terminal vowel (*-a* or *-o*) from the basic numerical term.
[src:alkane/alkane] The numeral prefix is generally Greek; however, alkanes with a carbon atom count ending in nine, for example nonane, use the Latin prefix **non-**.
[src:alkane/alkane] Simple branched alkanes often have a common name using a prefix to distinguish them from linear alkanes, for example *n*-butane, isobutane (or *i*-butane) for the two isomers of butane and *n*-pentane, isopentane, neopentane for the three isomers of pentane.
[src:alkane/alkane] IUPAC naming conventions can be used to produce a systematic name.
[src:alkane/alkane] Though technically distinct from the alkanes, this class of hydrocarbons is referred to by some as the "cyclic alkanes." As their description implies, they contain one or more rings.
[src:alkane/alkane] Simple cycloalkanes have a prefix "cyclo-" to distinguish them from alkanes.
[src:alkane/alkane] Cycloalkanes are named as per their acyclic counterparts with respect to the number of carbon atoms in their backbones, e.g., cyclopentane (C5H10) is a cycloalkane with 5 carbon atoms just like pentane (C5H12), but they are joined up in a five-membered ring.
[src:alkane/alkane] In a similar manner, propane and cyclopropane, butane and cyclobutane, etc.
[src:alkane/alkane] Substituted cycloalkanes are named similarly to substituted alkanes – the cycloalkane ring is stated, and the substituents are according to their position on the ring, with the numbering decided by the Cahn–Ingold–Prelog priority rules.
[src:alkane/alkane] The trivial (non-systematic) name for alkanes is "paraffins".
[src:alkane/alkane] Together, alkanes are known as the "paraffin series".
[src:alkane/alkane] Trivial names for compounds are usually historical artifacts.
[src:alkane/alkane] They were coined before the development of systematic names, and have been retained due to familiar usage in industry.
[src:alkane/alkane] Cycloalkanes are also called naphthenes.
[src:alkane/alkane] Branched-chain alkanes are called **isoparaffins**.
[src:alkane/alkane] "Paraffin" is a general term and often does not distinguish between pure compounds and mixtures of isomers, i.e., compounds of the same chemical formula, e.g., pentane and isopentane.
[src:alkane/alkane] Alkanes with the lowest molecular weights are gases, those of intermediate molecular weight are liquids, and the heaviest are waxy solids.
[src:alkane/alkane] Alkanes experiences intermolecular van der Waals forces.
[src:alkane/alkane] The cumulative effects of these intermolecular forces give rise to greater boiling points of alkanes.
[src:alkane/alkane] Under standard conditions, from CH4 to C4H10 alkanes are gaseous; from C5H12 to C17H36 they are liquids; and after C18H38 they are solids.
[src:alkane/alkane] As the boiling point of alkanes is primarily determined by weight, it should not be a surprise that the boiling point has an almost linear relationship with the size (molecular weight) of the molecule.
[src:alkane/alkane] As a rule of thumb, the boiling point rises 20–30 °C for each carbon added to the chain; this rule applies to other homologous series.
[src:alkane/alkane] A straight-chain alkane will have a boiling point higher than a branched-chain alkane due to the greater surface area in contact, and thus greater van der Waals forces, between adjacent molecules.
[src:alkane/alkane] For example, compare isobutane (2-methylpropane) and *n*-butane, which boil at −12 and 0 °C, and 2,2-dimethylbutane and 2,3-dimethylbutane which boil at 50 and 58 °C, respectively.
[src:alkane/alkane] On the other hand, cycloalkanes tend to have higher boiling points than their linear counterparts due to the locked conformations of the molecules, which give a plane of intermolecular contact.
[src:alkane/alkane] The melting points of the alkanes follow a similar trend to boiling points for the same reason as outlined above.
[src:alkane/alkane] That is, (all other things being equal) the larger the molecule the higher the melting point.
[src:alkane/alkane] However, alkanes' melting points follow a more complex pattern, due to variations in the properties of their solid crystals.
[src:alkane/alkane] One difference in crystal structure that even-numbered alkanes (from hexane onwards) tend to form denser-packed crystals compared to their odd-numbered neighbors.
[src:alkane/alkane] This causes them to have a greater enthalpy of fusion (amount of energy required to melt them), raising their melting point.
[src:alkane/alkane] A second difference in crystal structure is that even-numbered alkanes (from octane onwards) tend to form more rotationally ordered crystals compared to their odd-numbered neighbors.
[src:alkane/alkane] This causes them to have a greater entropy of fusion (increase in disorder from the solid to the liquid state), lowering their melting point.
[src:alkane/alkane] While these effects operate in opposing directions, the first effect tends to be slightly stronger, leading even-numbered alkanes to have slightly higher melting points than the average of their odd-numbered neighbors.
[src:alkane/alkane] This trend does not apply to methane, which has an unusually high melting point, higher than both ethane and propane.
[src:alkane/alkane] This is because it has a very low entropy of fusion, attributable to its high molecular symmetry and the rotational disorder in solid methane near its melting point (Methane I).
[src:alkane/alkane] The melting points of branched-chain alkanes can be either higher or lower than those of the corresponding straight-chain alkanes, again depending on these two factors.
[src:alkane/alkane] More symmetric alkanes tend towards higher melting points, due to enthalpic effects when they form ordered crystals, and entropic effects when they form disordered crystals (e.g. neopentane).
[src:alkane/alkane] Alkanes do not conduct electricity in any way, nor are they substantially polarized by an electric field.
[src:alkane/alkane] For this reason, they do not form hydrogen bonds and are insoluble in polar solvents such as water.
[src:alkane/alkane] Since the hydrogen bonds between individual water molecules are aligned away from an alkane molecule, the coexistence of an alkane and water leads to an increase in molecular order (a reduction in entropy).
[src:alkane/alkane] As there is no significant bonding between water molecules and alkane molecules, the second law of thermodynamics suggests that this reduction in entropy should be minimized by minimizing the contact between alkane and water: Alkanes are said to be hydrophobic as they are insoluble in water.
[src:alkane/alkane] Their solubility in nonpolar solvents is relatively high, a property that is called lipophilicity.
[src:alkane/alkane] Alkanes are, for example, miscible in all proportions among themselves.
[src:alkane/alkane] The density of the alkanes usually increases with the number of carbon atoms but remains less than that of water.
[src:alkane/alkane] Hence, alkanes form the upper layer in an alkane–water mixture.
[src:alkane/alkane] The molecular structure of the alkanes directly affects their physical and chemical characteristics.
[src:alkane/alkane] It is derived from the electron configuration of carbon, which has four valence electrons.
[src:alkane/alkane] The carbon atoms in alkanes are described as sp3 hybrids; that is to say that, to a good approximation, the valence electrons are in orbitals directed towards the corners of a tetrahedron which are derived from the combination of the 2s orbital and the three 2p orbitals.
[src:alkane/alkane] This is exact for the case of methane, while larger alkanes containing a combination of C–H and C–C bonds generally have bonds that are within several degrees of this idealized value.
[src:alkane/alkane] An alkane has only C–H and C–C single bonds.
[src:alkane/alkane] The former result from the overlap of an sp3 orbital of carbon with the 1s orbital of a hydrogen; the latter by the overlap of two sp3 orbitals on adjacent carbon atoms.
[src:alkane/alkane] The bond lengths amount to 1.09 × 10−10 m for a C–H bond and 1.54 × 10−10 m for a C–C bond.
[src:alkane/alkane] The spatial arrangement of the bonds is similar to that of the four sp3 orbitals—they are tetrahedrally arranged, with an angle of 109.47° between them.
[src:alkane/alkane] Structural formulae that represent the bonds as being at right angles to one another, while both common and useful, do not accurately depict the geometry.
[src:alkane/alkane] The spatial arrangement of the C-C and C-H bonds are described by the torsion angles of the molecule, known as its conformation.
[src:alkane/alkane] In ethane, the simplest case for studying the conformation of alkanes, there is nearly free rotation about a carbon–carbon single bond.
[src:alkane/alkane] Two limiting conformations are important: eclipsed conformation and staggered conformation.
[src:alkane/alkane] The staggered conformation is 12.6 kJ/mol (3.0 kcal/mol) lower in energy (more stable) than the eclipsed conformation (the least stable).
[src:alkane/alkane] In highly branched alkanes, the bond angle may differ from the optimal value (109.5°) to accommodate bulky groups.
[src:alkane/alkane] Such distortions introduce a tension in the molecule, known as steric hindrance or strain.
[src:alkane/alkane] Strain substantially increases reactivity.
[src:alkane/alkane] Spectroscopic signatures for alkanes are obtainable by the major characterization techniques.
[src:alkane/alkane] The C-H stretching mode gives strong absorptions between 2850 and 2960 cm−1 and weaker bands for the C-C stretching mode absorbs between 800 and 1300 cm−1.
[src:alkane/alkane] The carbon–hydrogen bending modes depend on the nature of the group: methyl groups show bands at 1450 cm−1 and 1375 cm−1, while methylene groups show bands at 1465 cm−1 and 1450 cm−1.
[src:alkane/alkane] Carbon chains with more than four carbon atoms show a weak absorption at around 725 cm−1.
[src:alkane/alkane] The proton resonances of alkanes are usually found at *δ*H = 0.5–1.5.
[src:alkane/alkane] The carbon-13 resonances depend on the number of hydrogen atoms attached to the carbon: *δ*C = 8–30 (primary, methyl, –CH3), 15–55 (secondary, methylene, –CH2–), 20–60 (tertiary, methyne, C–H) and quaternary.
[src:alkane/alkane] The carbon-13 resonance of quaternary carbon atoms is characteristically weak, due to the lack of nuclear Overhauser effect and the long relaxation time, and can be missed in weak samples, or samples that have not been run for a sufficiently long time.
[src:alkane/alkane] Since alkanes have high ionization energies, their electron impact mass spectra show weak currents for their molecular ions.
[src:alkane/alkane] The fragmentation pattern can be difficult to interpret, but in the case of branched chain alkanes, the carbon chain is preferentially cleaved at tertiary or quaternary carbons due to the relative stability of the resulting free radicals.
[src:alkane/alkane] The mass spectra for straight-chain alkanes is illustrated by that for dodecane: the fragment resulting from the loss of a single methyl group (*M* − 15) is absent, fragments are more intense than the molecular ion and are spaced by intervals of 14 mass units, corresponding to loss of CH2 groups.
[src:alkane/alkane] Alkanes are only weakly reactive with most chemical compounds.
[src:alkane/alkane] They only react with the strongest of electrophilic reagents by virtue of their strong C–H bonds (~100 kcal/mol) and C–C bonds (~90 kcal/mol).
[src:alkane/alkane] They are also relatively unreactive toward free radicals.
[src:alkane/alkane] This inertness is the source of the term *paraffins* (with the meaning here of "lacking affinity").
[src:alkane/alkane] In crude oil the alkane molecules have remained chemically unchanged for millions of years.
[src:alkane/alkane] The acid dissociation constant (p*K*a) values of all alkanes are estimated to range from 50 to 70, depending on the extrapolation method, hence they are extremely weak acids that are practically inert to bases (see: carbon acids).
[src:alkane/alkane] They are also extremely weak bases, undergoing no observable protonation in pure sulfuric acid (*H*0 ~ −12), although superacids that are at least millions of times stronger have been known to protonate them to give hypercoordinate alkanium ions (see: methanium ion).
[src:alkane/alkane] Thus, a mixture of antimony pentafluoride (SbF5) and fluorosulfonic acid (HSO3F), called magic acid, can protonate alkanes.
[src:alkane/alkane] All alkanes react with oxygen in a combustion reaction, although they become increasingly difficult to ignite as the number of carbon atoms increases.
[src:alkane/alkane] See the alkane heat of formation table for detailed data.
[src:alkane/alkane] The standard enthalpy change of combustion, Δc*H*⊖, for alkanes increases by about 650 kJ/mol per CH2 group.
[src:alkane/alkane] Branched-chain alkanes have lower values of Δc*H*⊖ than straight-chain alkanes of the same number of carbon atoms, and so can be seen to be somewhat more stable.
[src:alkane/alkane] Some organisms are capable of metabolizing alkanes.
[src:alkane/alkane] The methane monooxygenases convert methane to methanol.
[src:alkane/alkane] For higher alkanes, cytochrome P450 convert alkanes to alcohols, which are then susceptible to degradation.
[src:alkane/alkane] Free radicals, molecules with unpaired electrons, play a large role in most reactions of alkanes.
[src:alkane/alkane] Free radical halogenation reactions occur with halogens, leading to the production of haloalkanes.
[src:alkane/alkane] The hydrogen atoms of the alkane are progressively replaced by halogen atoms.
[src:alkane/alkane] The reaction of alkanes and fluorine is highly exothermic and can lead to an explosion.
[src:alkane/alkane] These reactions are an important industrial route to halogenated hydrocarbons.
[src:alkane/alkane] Experiments have shown that all halogenation produces a mixture of all possible isomers, indicating that all hydrogen atoms are susceptible to reaction.
[src:alkane/alkane] The mixture produced, however, is not statistical: Secondary and tertiary hydrogen atoms are preferentially replaced due to the greater stability of secondary and tertiary free-radicals.
[src:alkane/alkane] In the Reed reaction, sulfur dioxide and chlorine convert hydrocarbons to sulfonyl chlorides under the influence of light.
[src:alkane/alkane] Under some conditions, alkanes will undergo nitration.
[src:alkane/alkane] Certain transition metal complexes promote non-radical reactions with alkanes, resulting in C–H bond activation reactions.
[src:alkane/alkane] Cracking breaks larger molecules into smaller ones.
[src:alkane/alkane] This reaction requires heat and catalysts.
[src:alkane/alkane] The thermal cracking process follows a homolytic mechanism with formation of free radicals.
[src:alkane/alkane] The catalytic cracking process involves the presence of acid catalysts (usually solid acids such as silica-alumina and zeolites), which promote a heterolytic (asymmetric) breakage of bonds yielding pairs of ions of opposite charges, usually a carbocation.
[src:alkane/alkane] Carbon-localized free radicals and cations are both highly unstable and undergo processes of chain rearrangement, C–C scission in position beta (i.e., cracking) and intra- and intermolecular hydrogen transfer or hydride transfer.
[src:alkane/alkane] In both types of processes, the corresponding reactive intermediates (radicals, ions) are permanently regenerated, and thus they proceed by a self-propagating chain mechanism.
[src:alkane/alkane] The chain of reactions is eventually terminated by radical or ion recombination.
[src:alkane/alkane] Dragan and his colleague were the first to report about isomerization in alkanes.
[src:alkane/alkane] Isomerization and reformation are processes in which straight-chain alkanes are heated in the presence of a platinum catalyst.
[src:alkane/alkane] In isomerization, the alkanes become branched-chain isomers.
[src:alkane/alkane] In other words, it does not lose any carbons or hydrogens, keeping the same molecular weight.
[src:alkane/alkane] In reformation, the alkanes become cycloalkanes or aromatic hydrocarbons, giving off hydrogen as a by-product.
[src:alkane/alkane] Both of these processes raise the octane number of the substance.
[src:alkane/alkane] Butane is the most common alkane that is put under the process of isomerization, as it makes many branched alkanes with high octane numbers.
[src:alkane/alkane] In steam reforming, alkanes react with steam in the presence of a nickel catalyst to give hydrogen and carbon monoxide.
[src:alkane/alkane] Alkanes form a small portion of the atmospheres of the outer gas planets such as Jupiter (0.1% methane, 2 ppm ethane), Saturn (0.2% methane, 5 ppm ethane), Uranus (1.99% methane, 2.5 ppm ethane) and Neptune (1.5% methane, 1.5 ppm ethane).
[src:alkane/alkane] Titan (1.6% methane), a satellite of Saturn, was examined by the *Huygens* probe, which indicated that Titan's atmosphere periodically rains liquid methane onto the moon's surface.
[src:alkane/alkane] Also on Titan, the Cassini mission has imaged seasonal methane/ethane lakes near the polar regions of Titan.
[src:alkane/alkane] Methane and ethane have been detected in the tail of the comet Hyakutake.
[src:alkane/alkane] Chemical analysis showed that the abundances of ethane and methane were roughly equal, which is thought to imply that its ices formed in interstellar space, away from the Sun, which would have evaporated these volatile molecules.
[src:alkane/alkane] Alkanes have been detected in meteorites such as carbonaceous chondrites.
[src:alkane/alkane] Traces of methane gas (about 0.0002% or 1745 ppb) occur in the Earth's atmosphere, produced primarily by methanogenic microorganisms, such as Archaea in the gut of ruminants.
[src:alkane/alkane] The most important commercial sources for alkanes are natural gas and oil.
[src:alkane/alkane] Natural gas contains primarily methane and ethane, with some propane and butane: oil is a mixture of liquid alkanes and other hydrocarbons.
[src:alkane/alkane] These hydrocarbons were formed when marine animals and plants (zooplankton and phytoplankton) died and sank to the bottom of ancient seas and were covered with sediments in an anoxic environment and converted over many millions of years at high temperatures and high pressure to their current form.
[src:alkane/alkane] These hydrocarbon deposits, collected in porous rocks trapped beneath impermeable cap rocks, comprise commercial oil fields.
[src:alkane/alkane] They have formed over millions of years and once exhausted cannot be readily replaced.
[src:alkane/alkane] The depletion of these hydrocarbons reserves is the basis for what is known as the energy crisis.
[src:alkane/alkane] Alkanes have a low solubility in water, so the content in the oceans is negligible; however, at high pressures and low temperatures (such as at the bottom of the oceans), methane can co-crystallize with water to form a solid methane clathrate (methane hydrate).
[src:alkane/alkane] Although this cannot be commercially exploited at the present time, the amount of combustible energy of the known methane clathrate fields exceeds the energy content of all the natural gas and oil deposits put together.
[src:alkane/alkane] Methane extracted from methane clathrate is, therefore, a candidate for future fuels.
[src:alkane/alkane] Aside from petroleum and natural gas, alkanes occur significantly in nature only as methane, which is produced by some archaea by the process of methanogenesis.
[src:alkane/alkane] These organisms are found in the gut of termites and cows.
[src:alkane/alkane] The methane is produced from carbon dioxide or other organic compounds.
[src:alkane/alkane] It is probable that our current deposits of natural gas were formed in a similar way.
[src:alkane/alkane] Certain types of bacteria can metabolize alkanes: they prefer even-numbered carbon chains as they are easier to degrade than odd-numbered chains.
[src:alkane/alkane] Alkanes play a negligible role in higher organisms, with rare exception.
[src:alkane/alkane] Some yeasts, e.g., *Candida tropicale*, *Pichia* sp., *Rhodotorula* sp., can use alkanes as a source of carbon or energy.
[src:alkane/alkane] The fungus *Amorphotheca resinae* prefers the longer-chain alkanes in aviation fuel, and can cause serious problems for aircraft in tropical regions.
[src:alkane/alkane] In plants, the solid long-chain alkanes are found in the plant cuticle and epicuticular wax of many species, but are only rarely major constituents.
[src:alkane/alkane] They protect the plant against water loss, prevent the leaching of important minerals by the rain, and protect against bacteria, fungi, and harmful insects.
[src:alkane/alkane] The carbon chains in plant alkanes are usually odd-numbered, between 27 and 33 carbon atoms in length, and are made by the plants by decarboxylation of even-numbered fatty acids.
[src:alkane/alkane] The exact composition of the layer of wax is not only species-dependent but also changes with the season and such environmental factors as lighting conditions, temperature or humidity.
[src:alkane/alkane] The Jeffrey pine is noted for producing exceptionally high levels of *n*-heptane in its resin, for which reason its distillate was designated as the zero point for one octane rating.
[src:alkane/alkane] Floral scents have also long been known to contain volatile alkane components, and *n*-nonane is a significant component in the scent of some roses.
[src:alkane/alkane] Emission of gaseous and volatile alkanes such as ethane, pentane, and hexane by plants has also been documented at low levels, though they are not generally considered to be a major component of biogenic air pollution.
[src:alkane/alkane] Alkanes are important as pheromones, chemical messenger materials, on which insects depend for communication.
[src:alkane/alkane] 7-methyltricosane and 9-methyltricosane are active for ladybird beetles (*Adalia bipunctata*).
[src:alkane/alkane] The emerald ash borer (*Agrilus planipennis Fairmaire*) responds to 9-methylpentacosane.
[src:alkane/alkane] Female Asian long-horned beetles *Anoplophora glabripennis*, which are very damaging, secrete 2-methyldocosane.
[src:alkane/alkane] Waggle-dancing honey bees produce and release two alkanes, tricosane and pentacosane.
[src:alkane/alkane] One example, in which both plant and animal alkanes play a role, is the ecological relationship between the sand bee (*Andrena nigroaenea*) and the early spider orchid (*Ophrys sphegodes*); the latter is dependent for pollination on the former.
[src:alkane/alkane] Sand bees use pheromones in order to identify a mate; in the case of *A. nigroaenea*, the females emit a mixture of tricosane (C23H48), pentacosane (C25H52) and heptacosane (C27H56) in the ratio 3:3:1, and males are attracted by specifically this odor.
[src:alkane/alkane] The orchid takes advantage of this mating arrangement to get the male bee to collect and disseminate its pollen; parts of its flower not only resemble the appearance of sand bees but also produce large quantities of the three alkanes in the same ratio as female sand bees.
[src:alkane/alkane] As a result, numerous males are lured to the blooms and attempt to copulate with their imaginary partner: although this endeavor is not crowned with success for the bee, it allows the orchid to transfer its pollen, which will be dispersed after the departure of the frustrated male to other blooms.
[src:alkane/alkane] The most important source of alkanes is natural gas and crude oil.
[src:alkane/alkane] Alkanes are separated in an oil refinery by fractional distillation.
[src:alkane/alkane] Another route to alkanes is hydrogenolysis, which entails cleavage of C-heteroatom bonds using hydrogen.
[src:alkane/alkane] In industry, the main substrates are organonitrogen and organosulfur impurities, i.e. the heteroatoms are N and S.
[src:alkane/alkane] Hydrogenolysis can be applied to the conversion of virtually any functional group into hydrocarbons.
[src:alkane/alkane] Substrates include haloalkanes, alcohols, aldehydes, ketones, carboxylic acids, etc.
[src:alkane/alkane] Both hydrogenolysis and hydrogenation are practiced in refineries.
[src:alkane/alkane] They can be effected by using lithium aluminium hydride, Clemmenson reduction and other specialized routes.
[src:alkane/alkane] Coal is a more traditional precursor to alkanes.
[src:alkane/alkane] A wide range of technologies have been intensively practiced for centuries.
[src:alkane/alkane] Simply heating coal gives alkanes, leaving behind coke.
[src:alkane/alkane] Relevant technologies include the Bergius process and coal liquefaction.
[src:alkane/alkane] Partial combustion of coal and related solid organic compounds generates carbon monoxide, which can be hydrogenated using the Fischer–Tropsch process.
[src:alkane/alkane] This technology allows the synthesis of liquid hydrocarbons, including alkanes.
[src:alkane/alkane] This method is used to produce substitutes for petroleum distillates.
[src:alkane/alkane] Rarely is there any interest in the synthesis of alkanes, since they are usually commercially available and less valued than virtually any precursor.
[src:alkane/alkane] The best-known method is hydrogenation of alkenes.
[src:alkane/alkane] Many C−X bonds can be converted to C−H bonds using lithium aluminium hydride, Clemmenson reduction, and other specialized routes.
[src:alkane/alkane] Hydrolysis of alkyl Grignard reagents and alkyl organolithium reagents gives alkanes.
[src:alkane/alkane] The dominant use of alkanes is as fuels.
[src:alkane/alkane] Propane and butane, easily liquified gases, are commonly known as liquified petroleum gas (LPG).
[src:alkane/alkane] From pentane to octane the alkanes are highly volatile liquids.
[src:alkane/alkane] They are used as fuels in internal combustion engines, as they vaporize easily on entry into the combustion chamber without forming droplets, which would impair the uniformity of the combustion.
[src:alkane/alkane] Branched-chain alkanes are preferred as they are much less prone to premature ignition, which causes knocking, than their straight-chain homologues.
[src:alkane/alkane] This propensity to premature ignition is measured by the octane rating of the fuel, where 2,2,4-trimethylpentane (*isooctane*) has an arbitrary value of 100, and heptane has a value of zero.
[src:alkane/alkane] Apart from their use as fuels, the middle alkanes are also good solvents for nonpolar substances.
[src:alkane/alkane] Alkanes from nonane to, for instance, hexadecane (an alkane with sixteen carbon atoms) are liquids of higher viscosity, less and less suitable for use in gasoline.
[src:alkane/alkane] They form instead the major part of diesel and aviation fuel.
[src:alkane/alkane] Diesel fuels are characterized by their cetane number, cetane being an old name for hexadecane.
[src:alkane/alkane] However, the higher melting points of these alkanes can cause problems at low temperatures and in polar regions, where the fuel becomes too thick to flow correctly.
[src:alkane/alkane] By the process of cracking, alkanes can be converted to alkenes.
[src:alkane/alkane] Simple alkenes are precursors to polymers, such as polyethylene and polypropylene.
[src:alkane/alkane] When the cracking is taken to extremes, alkanes can be converted to carbon black, which is a significant tire component.
[src:alkane/alkane] Chlorination of methane gives chloromethanes, which are used as solvents and building blocks for complex compounds.
[src:alkane/alkane] Similarly treatment of methane with sulfur gives carbon disulfide.
[src:alkane/alkane] Still other chemicals are prepared by reaction with sulfur trioxide and nitric oxide.
[src:alkane/alkane] Some light hydrocarbons are used as aerosol sprays.
[src:alkane/alkane] Alkanes from hexadecane upwards form the most important components of fuel oil and lubricating oil.
[src:alkane/alkane] In the latter function, they work at the same time as anti-corrosive agents, as their hydrophobic nature means that water cannot reach the metal surface.
[src:alkane/alkane] Many solid alkanes find use as paraffin wax, for example, in candles.
[src:alkane/alkane] This should not be confused however with true wax, which consists primarily of esters.
[src:alkane/alkane] Alkanes with a chain length of approximately 35 or more carbon atoms are found in bitumen, used, for example, in road surfacing.
[src:alkane/alkane] However, the higher alkanes have little value and are usually split into lower alkanes by cracking.
[src:alkane/alkane] Alkanes are highly flammable, but they have low toxicities.
[src:alkane/alkane] Methane "is toxicologically virtually inert".
[src:alkane/alkane] Alkanes can be asphyxiants and narcotic.
